   309	                                  POST SCRIPT
   310	
   311	Many modem users have voiced confusion and consternation about the lack of
   312	compatibility between modem manufacturers at speeds greater than 2400 bps.
   313	
   314	Modem manufacturers have embraced the Bell 212A and 103 standards for 1200 and
   315	300 bps.  In these post-divestiture days, however, Bell no longer sets modem
   316	standards in the U.S. and hence, U.S. modem manufacturers have turned to the
   317	CCITT as a definitive source for standards.  The industry-wide acceptance of
   318	the CCITT's V.22bis standard for 2400 bps is the best example of this shift.
   319	
   320	The CCITT recommendations V.29 and V.32 for 9600 bps have not resulted in
   321	compatible implementations.  It is important to remember that V.29 was
   322	originally developed as a four-wire full duplex leased-line modem and has
   323	since been adapted by various manufacturers to encompass half duplex dial up
   324	applications.  Other problems with V.29 are that it compromises transmission
   325	speed and is poor for interactive sessions.  V.32 is proving to be
   326	prohibitively complex and exceptionally difficult to implement (driving
   327	development and production costs up).
   328	
   329	Recognizing the need for an alternative to the V.32 recommendation, the CCITT
   330	has requested proposals from modem manufacturers.
   331	
   332	Presently, two proposals are being considered by the CCITT.  One is the multi-
   333	carrier scheme developed and sponsored by Telebit.  The other is an
   334	Asymmetrical Frequency Division scheme developed and sponsored by USRobotics.
